          ],
          "key": "2ovvi",
          "text": "Oh man, there is nothing I love more than a big, long, thick biography. Last month, we talked about short books you could finish on a plane, well I’m talking about the opposite of that now, the ones that might take months to finish, even a year. But when you do, you’ve not only learned about a person but a whole sweeping period of history and all the people they intersected with. My life has been so changed by these books–not just because they made me a better reader for wrestling with them, but because of what I’ve learned from them about life and about writing. The rabbit holes they’ve taken me and my family down too! I was just driving my kids home from a camping trip in Garner State Park and where did we have to stop? Lyndon Johnson’s Ranch of course! If you had told me in 2016 when I started Robert Caro’s 3,500 page, four book series on LBJ that I’d still be fascinated by Johnson a decade later, I wouldn’t have believed you. But that’s what a great writer can do. Despite the length, his books fly by and you learn something about history, human nature, and power on almost every page. His intricate, complicated, sprawling investigation into Lyndon Johnson will change how you see ambition, politics, personality and justice. In any case, that brings me to the rest of the books in this month’s list. Oh, but before I do, I should mention I’m going to be on a Stoicism speaking tour this summer and fall–Portland, SF, Chicago, Minneapolis, Detroit plus a bunch of dates in Australia and New Zealand. Come see me, we can swap book recommendations!",
          "type": "unstyled"
        },
