          "key": "tim2",
          "text": "​Parting the Waters: America in the King Years 1954-63, Pillar of Fire: America in the King Years 1963-65, and At Canaan’s Edge: America in the King Years 1965-68 by Taylor Branch (2,300+ pages)\n​One of the best things you can do if you want to understand the current moment is to study the past. It’s why I picked up Taylor Branch’s epic three-part biography on Martin Luther King Jr. back in 2020, an experience that was life-changing. I was once again profoundly impacted by this series as I picked it back up to do research for Right Thing, Right Now. This trilogy does a phenomenal job of revealing the ways that an individual person really can have an impact on the collective, like Rev. James Lawson’s leadership at the Nashville sit-ins and Bayard Rustin’s role in the March on Washington. It’s also perfect for someone who is trying to master themselves because the civil rights leaders needed to be cool under pressure, under threat, under fear and had to be willing to act courageously in the pursuit of justice. It’s a masterpiece of a series, made even better by the fact that Branch began the series when his son was born, and finished it with the help of that same son years later (read more about that here). When you finish these, you absolutely have to pick up David Halberstam’s The Children.",
          "type": "unstyled"
        },
        {
