          "key": "ae76b",
          "text": "​1929: The Inside Story of the Greatest Crash in Wall Street History by Andrew Ross Sorkin (592 pages)\n​My first question when Andrew came on the podcast was how he managed to find the time to write this book between writing and editing for The New York Times and co-anchoring CNBC's Squawk Box. And even more impressively, it’s really good! The characters are great. The story is well-paced. It runs us through the crash in what feels like real-time with the chapters organized chronologically by specific dates. It’s one of those books that’s both timely, considering the crisis in Iran and the AI bubble, and timeless. Or perhaps you could say it is so timely because it is rooted in timeless themes. It reminded me a lot of another book I love about this period, Rising Tide: The Great Mississippi Flood of 1927 and How It Changed America, which also featured Herbert Hoover (but as the hero instead of the villain).",
          "type": "unstyled"
        },
