          "key": "9te46",
          "text": "​The Warmth of Other Suns: The Epic Story of America's Great Migration by Isabel Wilkerson (640 pages)\n​This is one of my absolute favorite books about American history. It reads almost like a giant Russian novel, but it’s about generations of Americans fleeing for a better life–not from overseas, but from the Deep South. This beautiful, painful and eye-opening look at the Great Migration looks at the biographical sketches of individuals who left the Jim Crow South for a chance at a better life in California, in Chicago, in New York City. Our own history–in America or anywhere in the world–is not a list of the things we’re proud of. It is a list of the things that happened. To get better, to improve, to get closer to ‘a more perfect union,’ we have to gather and put up for review an unflinching history. It’s not always fun…but it’s the only way. This book is an epic masterpiece that everyone should read. Wilkerson’s other book, Caste, is another one of my favorite books. And speaking of “caste,” I was blown away by Ramachandra Guha’s biography of Gandhi, Gandhi Before India which, like Parting the Waters, shows how the great man became the great man who changed the world. We tend to think of these activists at their moment of peak influence and forget that they built their movements from nothing…and I was most moved by Gandhi’s evolution, particularly on the issue of caste.",
          "type": "unstyled"
        },
