          "key": "bnr3g",
          "text": "​The Personal Memoirs of Ulysses S. Grant: The Complete Annotated Edition by Ulysses S. Grant and Team of Rivals: The Political Genius of Abraham Lincoln by Doris Kearns Goodwin\n​Grant’s memoirs are one of the most incredible stories in the history of publishing. How does one of America’s greatest generals and Presidents end up losing everything? His money is stolen from a crooked Wall Street operator, he’s dying of cancer, and he’s looking at leaving his family nothing. On the verge of his death, Mark Twain–who hated what publishers had done to Grant–approaches him with a self-publishing deal. Grant rushes to finish these memoirs and dies only a few days after they finish. Now, they’re one of the bestselling memoirs in American history. I would add that it’s one of the best memoirs in American history. It reveals the arc of an incredible American life: he graduates from West Point, goes on to be a hero of the Mexican-American War, only to plunge into alcoholism and ends up selling firewood on the side of the road. Within a few years, he’s not just a general back in the army, but he leads the Union cause to victory in the Civil War. He had a strategic vision, a determination, a perseverance, that made him the right man at the right moment so that he, along with Lincoln, managed to triumph over the Confederacy. It’s incredible. Every American should read this book. And then they should pick up Team of Rivals, which is a riveting 944-page book that captures the paradoxes that Lincoln embodies: He was both a wise man and a savvy politician, a good person and an ambitious one. I could say more, but I think the fact that I could justify lugging this book on a roundtrip of 16,928 miles to Australia a couple years back for the Stoic Life Tour (I’m actually headed back there in the fall for another tour, so if you missed me last I was in Australia or want to see me live on stage again, you can get tickets here), plus all the coffee shops and beaches I carried it to, tucked under my arm, says enough!",
          "type": "unstyled"
        },
