          "key": "6n8t2",
          "text": "​The Count of Monte Cristo by Alexandre Dumas (1,312 pages)\n​I didn’t want this list to JUST be biographies, although that’s my favorite style. I thought I’d read this book before but clearly it was some sort of children’s version, because this 1,312 page epic has some of the most brilliant, beautiful and complicated storytelling. What a book! I was riveted from cover to cover. I enjoyed all the stuff I missed as a kid: the Count’s struggle with his faith in light of what was done to him, the Hundred Days of Napoleon’s return, his rants against technology, the criticism of newspapers, the influence of ancient philosophy, ultimately, a warning against being consumed by revenge. Which is fitting, because I read it while I wrote my book Conspiracy. And if you haven’t read The Black Count, pick that one up after finishing The Count of Monte Cristo. It’s a biography by Tom Reiss about Alexandre Dumas’ father, who was a Black General under Napoleon. This book tells the incredible story of his life and reveals a side of French history I hadn’t learned otherwise.",
          "type": "unstyled"
        },
